LAGOS  – The Chairman and Managing Director of Chevron companies in Nigeria, Rick Kennedy, has stated that the company’s recent award and recognition underscore its commitment to compliance and high ethical standards in its operations. Chevron Nigeria Limited (CNL), operator of the joint venture between the Nigerian National Petroleum Company Limited (NNPC) and CNL (NNPC/CNL JV), and Star Deep Water Petroleum Limited (STAR), a Chevron company and operator of the Agbami field, were honoured by the Federal Inland Revenue Service (FIRS) with top tax compliant organization awards. The two Chevron companies were recognised among the awardees for 2021 at the Second Annual National Tax Dialogue organized by the Federal Inland Revenue Service at the Presidential Villa in Abuja. Rick said: “Chevron is committed to discharging its statutory fiscal obligations by ensuring strict compliance with all applicable Tax Laws and related regulations in the country” Esimaje Brikinn, CNL’s General Manager, Policy, Government and Public Affairs, while speaking on the award, explains that the award and recognition further affirm Chevron’s commitment to being a good corporate citizen in countries where it operates. “One of our core values is integrity and trust. We are honest with ourselves and others and honor our commitments. We earn the trust of partners and stakeholders by operating with the highest ethical standards in all we do,” he said. He thanked the FIRS for the recognition and assured that the company would continue to live up to its vision to be the global energy company most admired for its people, partnership, and performance. At the event declared open by President Muhammadu Buhari, FIRS emphasised that the recognition was for the remarkable performance by the companies in remittance of various taxes.